segments.text: What different battles did you, during the Tet, when were you wounded during what year?
Right at the heart of the Tet event.
And, well, I was wounded twice.
I was wounded in 65.
You know, I stepped on that mine and I was paralyzed for 10 months.
And I declared never to walk again, but I did, you know, because of faith.
Because of determination, and that's why I'm
I tell these youngsters in schools when I go.
I spoke to Texas A&M.
Did you know about that?
Yeah, he said he thought that you had been on campus.
I spoke to those Aggies.
In fact, they were getting me mad because I didn't know of the way that they have a way of approving and disapproving of your remarks.
And I was getting that whoop, whoop, whoop, whoop.
And I thought they were making fun of me.
You didn't know that the Aggie whoop, whoop meant that it was good, huh?
That's right.
And especially, I got a real whoop-whoop when I said, one of the song micromanagers who was a graduate of Texas A&M, of A&M, that I learned two things.
Either to follow, leave, or drink beer and get the hell out of the way.
He said, whoop-whoop, whoop-whoop, whoop.
No, I don't know what...
about the question that you asked?
When you were wounded?
When I was wounded?
Okay.
I didn't know.
I was completely sorry in 1965.
I never find out anything.
I'm supposed to meet a guy that's 20 years in San Antonio, Texas, who said I saved his life.
I don't know how I saved his life, because I don't remember.
I woke up in the Philippine Islands in Glock Air Force Base.
And I was paralyzed.
And I brought myself together.
I used to stand up.
Did you see that show that I did for real people?
No, I didn't get to see that.
Yeah, it showed, you know, at the 100th grade.
I'd drop out of bed and crawl up to the wall and back myself and pick up myself and stand there and try to move my toes.
And I did that for 10 months, boy.
Sometimes the nurses would catch me, you know, and they'd give me a pill and a shot and put me to sleep.
But the doctor said that I never walked again.
And I walked out of the hospital.
Thank God I did.
I went back in 68.
I volunteered.
I made three pressure jumps in one day after I got out of the hospital.
I brought myself physically in.
You know, it's willpower that a person should have.
That's why I tell these youngsters, you know, there's faith.
And I ask them, what are the very first words that you utter when you need help?
Oh my God.
And that's you.
If you want something done, you'll find a way.
I was taught in the schools and in the Army, especially in the Air Force, that quitters never win and winners never quit.
So I'm a winner.
And in that show of real people, I was speaking at a school, and a little girl came in and asked a question as to, you know, after I'd been shot up six, seven times and band-aids and so forth,
I thought about giving up.
And I told her, I said, no, honey, I said, don't marry, don't never give up.
I mean, that's just the way I feel.
You know, you fight the last drop.
I mean, that enemy is just like you.
You're better training him, so it's you or him.
Then in 68, then I went back.
Uh, that, uh, Dan Masek was one of the volunteers to go get those, those men out.
It was a, it was a trip of no return.
And because the whole darn mission was already, it's, it was a highly classified mission.
And there was no return in any company.
They shut off the operation.
But those poor guys, they needed help.
And I'm glad that the other helicopter that came over to my area didn't know about that.
There was no other helicopter before that.
Which eventually they went later.
Maybe we could have saved some more.
What unit were you with?
I was the Taxman B-56 Sigma of the 5th Special Forces.
We were in the Intelligence Reconference Team.
We were trained to gather information from the enemy, the size, the location, and the morale.
We went on some long, lonely missions at times, away behind lines.
And we got pretty good information.
That was during the, there was more of that.
But see, it's what really gets me that they're only questioning those that were right there on the staff.
They're not questioning the people that were feeding the information to them.
Those are the men that know.
I mean, whether one of these men back over here on the staff
Well, had it in for the general and he would make it up and no one knows.
No one knows.
False information.
He had no way of knowing whether the information was true or not.
That's right.

He just had to go, he had to depend on the people under him to... Well, you see that plaque that I have and that's what, that's what that commentator, that plaque of West Point that I have right under the president now, uh, uh,
One of the commentators, reporters in that CBS network, when the general got very disappointed, and he got a little bit disturbed when he said that his integrity had been insulted.
And that reporter reminded the general of the code of West Point Census.
The general was a West Point graduate.
And the code, duty, honor, and country.
A cadet does not lie, cheat, or steal, or tolerate those that do.
Now that, to me, I was trained by Westmoreland.
I had commanders, and I lived by that code also.
Anyone that comes next, they don't know what they're talking about.
I hope he wins the case.
But my question is, how come we're not interviewed?
Us that were gathering intelligence and information.
They have just as much top secret plans as we have.
But I bet you if they would, then they'd really know the truth.
They're going to be very selective on who they interview.
Well, probably so.
Probably.
It's one thing that we have, that some professionals have, that we're not out to glorify ourselves when we come into contact with you.
We're out to help one another.
I mean, if I'm asked, did you do this, did you do that?
Yes, I did.
I'm not going to say that he ordered me.
Because maybe in his staff meetings, he wasn't told exactly everything, the way things were going back then.
You said that you attended the Memorial Day services in Washington when they unveiled the new monument and everything.
Do you think that it's a worthy monument to the Vietnam veterans?
I think it is.
It is a symbol of gratitude.
I think that the public that goes there sense that thoughtfulness.
And in a way, they're trying to, well, we put it on ourselves.
We work for it ourselves.
We just want to show the public, hey,
We're doing this for our own self.
I mean, you neglected it now.
But now they want to, you should have seen it, I tell you, there in those restaurants and those bars.
Even the cab drivers would give them a free ride.
Because they knew, they knew the way the others were treated there.
And there's people that go there and they take pictures
that people would just stand there with tears in their eyes.
Whether they had a son that died in Vietnam or not, but the kid next door, the guy that lived with, that little boy, just like John that lives across from us, you know, we love that little kid.
Not only because he's the only son in the family, but he comes, you know, and we move here.
He comes to stay with us, he comes to eat here, and everything.
And, uh,
I won't say too much about the other name.
Do you think it's significant on the monument that it has a black man?
No, I don't think it's that much.
I think it's just that they, you know, we got what we wanted and we just wanted to put that.
I mean, we could have put a woman there.
You know, they'd serve too.
And probably they're trying to come up with the idea.
But what, are we going to put three women there too?
Because if three women serve,
Well, when I saw it on TV, you know, to me, I thought, well, you know,
It's really good that there's the white man, the black man, and the brown man, showing that it wasn't just one person fighting the war, that it was a unified thing between all the races.
It's like the stamp.
Did you see the Hispanic stamp?
No.
That's been an honor for them, and the honor was different.
When did you, so you left Vietnam in, in 68 after you were wounded.
And they, where did you go after that?
Well, I came, well, I came to three hospitals.
I came through Japan, and I came through California, and I landed in, in Fort Tampines, in the region of Virginia, in San Antonio.
How long were you in the hospital?
All total, from the time I got hit and then to about the time that I was released, I was over a year.
Where was your family at this time?
They were here in El Campo.
And when were you, when did you, after that, did you, were you still in the service?
When did you, were you discharged from the service?
No, I continue, you know, I got rehabilitated and I got, you know, thanks to the modern
technology and doctors, good doctors.
I was allowed to remain in the military.
I couldn't jump anymore out of airplanes and I couldn't be in the special forces anymore.
However, I did try.
When I was released, I was sent to...
I went to Fort Deven, Massachusetts with the 10 Special Forces group.
And that group there does some mountain training, mountain climbing, skiing.
Every group in the Special Forces has a different area of training and expertise.
Well, they're all trained in light and heavy weapons, engineering, mechanics, in operation intelligence, and communication.
But the different areas of the country, of the world, they're trained for those different parts.
They have a responsibility for parts of the world.
And I was there.
And then I found out I just couldn't jump anymore, and it hurt me.
It hurt myself.
So I was sent to Fort Ryder, Kansas.
And I was given a death jab, which I hated.
But still, you know, I was in the troop.
And I went to Europe on the Reef Hoarder exercise for seven weeks.
I loved it.
I really got out to the field.
Sometimes my commander, you know, he'd get mad a little bit.
But I wanted to be with the troops, you know, because I was a field soldier.
And I returned back.
I went, I stayed there two years in Kansas.
And then I was assigned to drive for a general, a commander.
And then I was transferred to Fort St. Houston.
How long were you in Fort St. Houston?
Well, I was there, I think, four years.
And until the general retired, and then I was given another assignment, which I persuaded them into letting me be an advisor to the reserve unit so I could be out and do the troops.
And they had special forces reserves, you know.
So, you know, they thought that, they didn't know the full extent of my health.
I wasn't about to tell them any time.
I'd rather hurt than be out there in the field, you know, than to be behind a desk, listening to telephones and everything.
And then my injuries started catching up with me naturally as I was getting older.
And there were some bad times that, you know, that I shouldn't really be enough to the field and exaggerate the training.
So I had to go on.
important, you know, get a physical.
And at times, the doctor, you know, he would tell me to say, that's it, you know, you're wasting yourself just because of the pride that you have of being a Green Maria.
Well, you know, either to or die.
But I was boarded out.
Five doctors came to a conclusion at eight.
You're not fit for military duty.
Let's face it.
It's not that you can't do it.
It's just that you can't do it by regulation.
So I thought that if these five doctors had concluded that, then why should I be putting a senior non-commissioned officer corps in the chamber?
Because when I was leading the troops, naturally, I had to set the example.
And you can't set no example by walking crippled or sitting down and letting the troops go by.
You have to be the first one up front and you have to be with them early in the morning.
You can't slow down.
You're sending a bad example.
So I had to accept that I did.
So after 25 years I said, hey, we're going to magically discharge you because they did.
In what year was that?

When did you find, when did you begin your, or find out about the Medal of Honor and start your... Well, I knew, I knew, I found out about that in, in 70, 73, when I was there in San Antonio before San Houston.
I met a
an officer that I had served with, my commander, and he knew of my action.
He was an intelligence officer.
And we had coffee one day, and he asked me about the medley.
I said, well, I didn't know nothing about it.
My commander thought I was dead, and everybody thought I was dead, all but him when he saw me there.
And then we, that was in the 70s,
We started the ball rolling, and we dug up the original recommendation, and they stated, you know, the Malabano was recommended, but an internal war was made.
And so, we had to start from scratch.
We had to find the commander again.
We found Colonel Drake.
We found him in Louisiana.
And...
Well, you know, of course, I drove down there to see him, and that was a moment I tell you.
In fact, he said that he wanted to take a picture that embraced him.
He said he never embraced his wife like that.
Of course, we were happy to see each other, you know.
And the last piece on was, I was floating in my own blood.
And I couldn't talk to him.
I could just wiggle my toes.
Then he reconstructed.
He didn't know the full extent of mine, actually.
He didn't know that I had volunteered to go.
Then he reconstructed me.
How long?
And then I had to find witnesses.
And I found an eyewitness.
It took me from 73 to 81.
You were awarded the, in that 1981 is when you were awarded the medal.
Yeah.
See, but it started from May of 68.
You just laid dormant all those years, and you didn't know anything about it.
Yeah, well, you see, that's why the people in the surrounding area came.
They thought that I was asking for the medal.
I just wanted to widen it, to dig up the record, and I need it.
Moral support, and I needed it from the veterans organization.
One organization said, and this was a very highly publicized veteran organization, and said, hey, we're not supposed to get involved with the ex-serviceman in the war.
Well, golly.
And the veterans organization, well, because this is local, they didn't want it.
Had my name been Jones or Mitchell, it would have been different.
Even though there's supposed to be no prejudice, there's still a lot of prejudice, isn't there?
A lot of jealousy.
Jealousy.
You have to consider the sources.
But it's hard.
It's hard.
It's hard for me and my kid, because he goes through the peer pressure.
I mean, what am I supposed to do?
get up and leave.
One of my neighbors, the kids, they can play together, but they can't step in her yard.
And yet her kids can run across my yard any time.
It's a shame that people have these jealousies and can't just accept everybody as they are.
What effects do you think of the separation from your family?
Did you, do you think there was any problems being separated from your family so long being in the service?
Do you think it's hard on, on wives and children to be dependents of servicemen?
Well, yeah, but see my wife, my wife knew that I, my career, of course we, we got, we were married when I began my career.
And I had told her, you know, I had explained to her, this is my life, this is my career.
You marry in the Army, you're not married to me.
So, you know, she accepted it, because I had sit down and talked this over, you know, friends we're gonna meet, places we're gonna travel to, and everything.
And before you, whatever, you can say no, or you can say yes.
There's no other work that I can do better than to be a soldier.
And I've learned a lot of skills.
That's why I tell the youngsters in school, I've learned a lot of good traits.
And I got my education in the military.
Not only traveling, but
I started my college education.
I got my high school diploma.
I went to an MP school.
I was an investigator.
I was an interpreter.
I am an interrogator.
I know fingerprint.
I know meteorology.
I know chemical warfare techniques.
I know foreign languages.
I could have never done nothing out here.
I'd have to pay for it.
The military paid for it.
I traveled at the expense of the taxpayers' money.
And I served my country.
I traveled all over the world.
So, yes, they had some sort of hardship, but then they understood.
And we've been back for 26 years now.
What hardship there was, I don't know.
At times I felt bad, yes.
But still, you know, she stayed behind me and I'm glad.
There's some broken marriages because they don't talk things and they don't want to.
And maybe it's best.
Maybe it's best to separate.
But there's some people that are cut out for certain jobs and that's it.
And everybody agrees on it.
And you don't fight the system.
It just happened that I got severely wounded, and the Army takes care of the military.
This government takes care of the veterans.
And so I'm happy to take care of it.
How do you spend your time now?
What is your main objective as far as working with the military or in any space that you can?
Oh, well, I, you know, I'm called to come and make speeches to various colleges and schools, ROTC's, and I'm writing my autobiography, you know, I have a Pulitzer Prize winner that goes right.
And I just enjoy my kids, you know, we stay together and we travel.
Just like, you know, the retired person.
But I like to, I don't like to, but I do go visit patients in the hospital, you know, veterans.
I hate to see them there because I remember my days, you know, there.
And I know what they're going through.
I know that some of these doctors, there's nothing they can do for them.
And I know some of these
Others, they're members of the family, they want everything done overnight.
I know some of these veterans, they're killed, they've been neglected through their benefits.
And so, they called on me to help them.
I had friends all over the country that advised me, lawyers and what not.
And I'd get someone and say, oh, women widows.
There's a lady that's having problems.
She works at the bank.
She's having problems with her husband.
Her husband, her brother-in-law, her husband's brother and I were in the service together.
And I walked in the bank one day, and I noticed a name.
And we talked.
We got acquainted.
And she said, yeah, I've heard a lot about you.
That my brother-in-law used to talk about you.
And so she asked me if I heard about it.
So I told her, I think she went to the proper authorities.
And you also said that you
that's something that's really important to you, is working with the POW and the MIA.
Yes, I'm involved with them.
In fact, I happened to write a letter to a guy in Anchorage, Alaska, that they want to get involved with a mine of bracelet, and he wants to set up a little program up there for the MIA.
There's a lady here in Palacios that I want to go see.
Her son's been missing since 1959, I think.
She doesn't know, you know, she's a Hispanic lady.
She doesn't know the benefits, the rights that she had with her mother.
And so I'm going to go in here and advise on that.
I, uh, I hope that, that, uh, you know, these, these, uh, students who get involved, uh, to help, uh, to call the right, uh, the, uh, government, North American government.
I mean, what?
What?
Why are we holding on to this?
These youngsters, just think, it's going to be Christmas.
How do you think some of these youngsters, they never knew their dad.
They were too little, they'd never seen him.
How can they be watching TV, singing Christmas carols and enjoying themselves when things would come to their mind about their dad sitting over there in some little wooden cage?
not knowing what day it is, and not even good about it.
How many MIAs do they, POWs do they think are still over there?
The last count that we had, there was 2,992, I think.
POWs?
Yeah.
I know there's 164 in Texas.
I've got all their names.
There are 16 Hispanic, 19 Hispanic.
Well, I'd like to thank you for sharing your life and story with us.
Thank you.
I hope you make an A.
And I've certainly enjoyed seeing all your posts.
beautiful things you have.
I've got some more since the last time.
See that big Indian right there?
Yeah.
That guy here with Chicago and the North.
